itle>Understanding Gendered Agency in Violent Conflict: Extending Conceptual and Methodological Parameters</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-451-25-4232-A</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The post Cold War era has seen the emergence of a general consensus
&lt;br />around the need to rethink war. In place of the ?classic? inter-state model,
&lt;br />there are conflicts with&amp;nbsp; very few actual engagements between organised
&lt;br />military forces.&amp;nbsp; The&amp;nbsp; battlegrounds are civilians? homes and combatants not
&lt;br />recognisable as national militaries.&amp;nbsp; This type of&amp;nbsp; violence can engulf entire
&lt;br />regions and produce new patterns of&amp;nbsp; national boundaries. These shifts in the realities of armed conflict have not just affected the military sector. Many humanitarian and development agencies now find themselve operating in conflict zones.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />These shifts all have implications for the study of gender relations,
&lt;br />particularly those&amp;nbsp; around conflict and violence. For example, women ?
&lt;br />especially mothers - have commonly been associated with a ?pro-peace?
&lt;br />position, and there are certainly many important initiatives of this
&lt;br />kind in conflict zones. However, at the same time, women have sustained
&lt;br />violent conflict in a number of ways. Despite&amp;nbsp; conventional assumptions
&lt;br />about male aggression, there are also&amp;nbsp; many instances of men
&lt;br />refusing/avoiding involvement in armed conflict.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />This seminar series will provide an opportunity to examine these shifts&amp;nbsp; in
&lt;br />detail and to relate them to current policy initiatives e.g. around sexual
&lt;br />violence in war.
&lt;br />
